Diagnostic binary for the `steno` crate: builds the real dictionary from `dict.steno` under six configurations (3 generic-arg pools × full-param vs. no-param function shapes) and prints a size matrix to stdout in whole KB. Writes no files; purely a reporting tool run manually to compare dictionary size tradeoffs.

The no-param variant works by string-matching each entry's `stroke_raw` against the hardcoded `NOPARAM` table and, on match, reparsing a fixed template string (with `%0`/`%1`/`%t`/`%b` placeholders, no `count`) to strip AOE param expansion — this table must be kept in sync by hand with whatever function-shape strokes currently exist in `dict.steno` (`STKWR-PBGS/-FLT`, `-R`, `-PL`, `-PB`, `-D`, `-F`); if those strokes are renamed or removed in the corpus, entries silently fall through to `None => Ok(e.clone())` and keep their param counts, silently skewing the "NO param" measurements without any error.

`POOLS` defines the three generic-arg restrictions compared (`None` = all 14 arity-0 strokes, or explicit stroke-name subsets like `&["STR", "TPH", "PW"]`); these stroke names must match whatever `expand_dict`'s pool-filtering logic expects.

Key entry points: `run() -> Result<(), String>` drives the whole matrix (reads `dict.steno` relative to `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../..`, i.e. assumes this binary lives two directories below the workspace root). `measure(label, entries, pool) -> Result<(), String>` expands one config via `expand_dict`, builds both `build_plain_dict` and `build_smart_dict`, and prints strokes/sizes/collisions for that one row. `kb(result) -> usize` computes JSON-serialized size via `to_json(&result.dict).len() / 1024` — integer division, so sizes under 1KB display as 0 and all values are floored, not rounded (this is intentional per the file's doc comment: "float arithmetic is disallowed here"). `collision_note` dedupes `result.collisions` through a `BTreeSet` before counting, so repeated collisions on the same key aren't over-counted.

Depends on the `steno` lib crate's public API (`Entry`, `BuildResult`, `parse_source`, `parse_template`, `expand_dict`, `build_plain_dict`, `build_smart_dict`, `to_json`) — any signature change there breaks this binary immediately.